observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management require the:
a. Municipal Engineer to provide the Accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation per road component of road networks in the municipality, and simultaneously conducting a physical inventory of the road networks;
b. Inventory Committee to conduct annual physical inventory of road networks and prepare the corresponding Report on Physical Count of Local Road Network (RPCLRN) in accordance with the format prescribed in Annex C of COA Circular No. 2015-008;
c. General Services Officer (GSO) to maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map, and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components; and
d. Municipal Accountant to keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components of every road network, and determine the corresponding depreciation thereof.

We recommended that Management ensure strict compliance with the rules and regulations on the granting, utilization, and liquidation of cash advances and:
a. Refrain from granting cash advances to elected officials other than for official travel purposes; 
b. Ensure that only duly appointed or designated disbursing officers perform disbursing functions; 
c. Require all officials and employees concerned to comply with the prescribed timeline on the liquidation of cash advances; and 
d. Enforce policy of not granting additional cash advance to officials and/or employees whose previous cash advance were not yet liquidated or not properly accounted for.

We recommended that Management direct the:
a. Concerned accountable officers (AOs) to return/surrender the unserviceable properties in their possession to the Property Officer for proper inspection and cancellation of the corresponding Property Acknowledgement Receipt (PAR) and/or Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS); 
b. Property Office to update the Inspection and Inventory Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) to include all unserviceable property and equipment, and prepare a separate Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Semi-Expendable Property (IIRUSP) for unserviceable semi-expendable items; 
c. Property Office to provide the Disposal Committee a copy of the duly accomplished and signed IIRUP and IIRUSP; and 
d. Disposal Committee to promptly evaluate the unserviceable properties and recommend to the Local Chief Executive the appropriate mode of disposal; and dispose of the unserviceable properties in accordance with prescribed rules and regulations on supply and property management.

We recommended that Management direct the MDRRM Office and MDRRM Council to:
a. Utilize the QRF during a state of calamity to enhance the Municipality's capacity to respond effectively to disasters;
b. Re-appropriate the budget for PPAs which are no longer feasible to other disaster related initiatives;
c. Properly plan and monitor the timely implementation of identified programs/projects/activities under the LDRRMF; and
d. Prepare a comprehensive LDRRMF Investment Plan which includes PPAs funded by current and prior years’ unexpended LDRRMF and ensure these PPAs are incorporated into the revised AIP and approved by the local sanggunian and LCE. 
We further recommended that utilization of the LDRRMF be strictly limited to expenses that directly contribute to disaster prevention and mitigation, preparedness, response, rehabilitation and recovery.

We recommended that henceforth, the Municipal Engineer:
a. Use the exact estimated duration of the activity for each work item to deter over-estimates in the Approved Budget for the Contract and Contract cost; 
b. Strictly comply with the DPWH Standard Pay Item List in the preparation of the Program of Works and Approved Budget for the contract; 
c. Ensure consistent use of unit prices for materials across different work items outlined in the Program of Works; and
d. Use factor one in deriving the quantity of materials pursuant to DPWH Department Order No. 207, Series of 2016 dated October 20, 2016.

5.5 We recommended that Management require the:
5.5.1 Inventory Committee to conduct an annual physical inventory of road networks to properly account for the LRN within the Municipality’s jurisdiction and prepare the corresponding RPCLRN;
5.5.2 Municipal Engineer to provide the Accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of road components for road projects;
5.5.3 General Services Officer (GSO) to maintain a Local Road Inventory and Road Map, and keep a complete Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components; and
5.5.4 Municipal Accountant to keep and maintain subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network, and to record in the books of accounts the completed road network projects and determine the corresponding depreciation of each road component.

5.6 We further recommended and Management agreed to ensure adherence with the accounting and reporting guidelines on the Local Road Asset Management System prescribed by COA Circular No. 2015-008 in order to come up with a reliable Local Road Network account balance in the financial statements.

11.4 We recommended that Management:
11.4.1 fast-track the implementation of the DRRAP, SFP and Repair of Mt. Pulag Barangay Health Station in order to achieve their objectives;
11.4.2 remit to the National Treasury the transferred funds amounting to ₱1,000,000.00 intended for the procurement of 1-unit ambulance pursuant to Local Budget Circular No. 128 dated September 17, 2020;
11.4.3 coordinate with the Department of Budget and Management on the appropriate action/s to be undertaken for the proper disposition of the KASF amounting to ₱305,408.00; and
11.4.4 require the implementing offices and the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all documents pertaining to projects funded by national government agencies are on file to provide basis in the implementation thereof.

We recommended the Municipal Treasurer:
a) to immediately deposit the undeposited collections with the AGDB;
b) to ensure that collections are deposited intact within the prescribed period pursuant to Section 32 of the NGAS Manual to prevent possible loss or misappropriation;
c) to require field collectors to remit collections at least once a week or as soon as their collections reach ₱5,000.00 pursuant to Section 29 of the NGAS Manual.
We further recommended the Treasury Management Office to ensure that all collections receipted for the year are completely reported in the Report of Collections and Deposits and transmitted to the Accounting Office on time for appropriate recording in the books of accounts to ascertain accuracy and reliability of financial information.

We recommended that Management:
a.) Revert the unutilized funds of the unimplemented ineligible projects for re-appropriation to other unimplemented ineligible development projects identified under Item 3 of JMC No. 2017-1;
b.) Henceforth, strictly follow the provisions of JMC No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017 in identifying PPAs to be funded out of the 20 percent MDF to ensure that desirable socio-economic development is attained.

We recommended that Management:
a.) Consider the quantity and nature of development projects being proposed for inclusion in the budget so that these are proportionate to the capacity of available resources, especially the manpower resources of the Municipal Engineering Office;
b.) Review the technical viability of prior years’ unimplemented PPAs to determine whether there is a need to re-appropriate the amount to other priority PPAs of the Municipality;
c.) Fast track the implementation of the unimplemented PPAs to bring development in the community for the welfare of the public; and
d.) Formulate/develop specific strategies/solutions to effectively implement development projects. Properly plan the timely implementation procurement and implementation of all identified priority development projects to ensure prompt accomplishment of the same.

